x4freetext: APSARA and CIRUS Research Reactor
For long-lived fission products electrodeposited
targets of 243-Am (~ 90 ug) were covered with 25 um
thick aluminum foil or 75 um thick Lexan foil, which
act as a catcher to collect the recoiling fission
products during the neutron irradiation of the
targets.
They were then wrapped with 1 mm thick cadmium foil,
doubly sealed in alkathene bags and irradiated for
about 5 to 60 min at a of flux 1.2 0E10*12 n/cm2-sec.
For short-lived fission products, the nitrate solution
of 243Am (~ 50 ug) were sealed in a polypropylene
tube and wrapped with 1 mm thick cadmium foil.
They were additionally sealed in alkathene bags and
irradiated using pneumatically carrier facility for
3 to 5 min at a flux of 5.0 0E10*12 n/cm2-sec.
Fission products were
collected using recoil catcher technique.
The aluminium catcher foils in APSARA irradiation was
used for radiochemical separation of tellurium and
iodine.
The irradiated solution in the CIRUS irradiation was
used for radiochemical separation of cesium.
The irradiated solutions, lexan catcher foils
separated aliquots of tellurium, iodine and cesium
were taken for gamma ray counting.
The fission products were analyzed by gamma ray
spectrometry at a fixed geometry of an energy- and
efficiency- calibrated 120 or 80-cm3 high-purity
germanium detector coupled to a PC-based 4K channel
analyzer.
The resolution of the detector system was 2.0 keV at
1332.0 keV and the dead time was always less than 10%.
The photo-peak areas of the gamma rays for the radio
nuclides were calculated from their total peak areas
by subtracting the Compton background.
From the photo-peak areas, independent isomeric yields
and thus their ratios were calculated using standard
decay growth equation after correcting for precursor
contribution.
The activities of 92-Sr and 104-Tc were used as
fission rate monitors in the long and short
irradiated un-separated samples respectively.
In the separated samples of tellurium, iodine and
cesium samples 134-Te, 135-I and 139-Cs were  used as
fission rate monitors respectively.
Independent isomeric yield ratio(IYR)of 128-Sb, 130-Sb,
and 138-Cs were determined in 243-Am(n,f) using
radiochemical and off line gamma ray spectrometric
techniques.
From the IYR fragment angular momenta (Jrms) were
deduced using spin dependent statistical model
analysis.

x4freetext: The uncertainty on the IYR includes the
error due to:
- counting statistics,
- absolute abundance of the gamma lines,
- detector efficiencies,
- the fission the yields of precursor
- the least square fit analysis.
